      "description": "DirectSum full128 (N1=N2=64, n_target_dims_per_block=[64, 64]),\nidentity init, additive coupling, split-mode loss. 12-run grid:\n3 LC \u2208 {1e-6, 1e-5, 1e-4} \u00d7 4 LPL \u2208 {1, 3, 10, 30}. Same data /\nobs noise / model arch as wmtask_direct_sum_additive_splitmode_p30\n_full128__lc_x_obsnoisescale_sweep \u2014 only LC and LPL vary.\n",
      "hypothesis": "The dynamics-MLP gradient-signal diagnostic showed DirectSum gets\n~2x less \u2202L/\u2202J_f than monolithic at trained state. The chain-rule\nstory attributes this to two rounds of block-diagonal Jacobian\nfiltering (encoder + decoder) on the obs loss. Latent prediction\nloss bypasses the decoder, so increasing its weight should\ncompensate. Predict:\n  - At LPL=1 (default), Lyapunov spectrum has the suppressed\n    negative tail we already observed.\n  - At higher LPL, negative tail extends closer to empirical\n    (\u0394\u03bb_min smaller) at the cost of slightly worse traj_loss\n    (because LPL competes with obs-rollout fidelity).\n  - Sweet spot probably exists where Lyapunov is fixed and\n    traj_loss is still acceptable (within 2x of LPL=1).\nLC kept tight around the previously-found best (1e-5) since LPL\nis the variable of interest.\n",
      "success_criteria": [
        "All 12 runs train without divergence",
        "Best-Lyapunov cell has \u0394\u03bb_min < 5 (vs current ~13 at LPL=1)",
        "Best-traj_loss cell within 2x of the original DS chosen-best (0.0044)"
      ]
    }
